[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["Itinerary banner.jpg"]]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["itinerary"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.nationaltrail.co.uk\/offas-dyke-path ",{"type":"'''","value":["Offa's Dyke Path"]}]}," (",{"type":"''","value":["Llwybr Clawdd Offa"]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Welsh phrasebook"],["Welsh"]]},") is a National Trail which runs through the varied landscapes of the Welsh Marches along or near the border of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Wales"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["England"]]}," between ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Prestatyn"]]}," on the Irish Sea in the north and Sedbury Cliffs on the Severn estuary near Chepstow in the south.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["File:Llwybr clawdd offa.jpg"],["thumb"],["Markers are not standardised"]]},"\nOffa's Dyke Path is a popular walking route through the border regions of England and Wales. The dyke itself (",{"type":"''","value":["Clawdd Offa"]}," in Welsh) has partially disappeared in places, although in the parts where it is preserved, it's about 20m wide and 2.5m high. In particular, there is an 130km (80mi) section between the Wye Valley and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Wrexham"]]}," where the Dyke is easily seen. The route is approximately 289km (177mi) in length, and takes between 12 to 14 days. The path was inaugurated in 1971 and an estimated ??? people walk the route each year.\n\nMuch of the history of the Dyke is based on some speculation, but it is named after ",{"type":"[[","value":[[":w:Offa of Mercia"],["Offa, King of Mercia"]]}," between 757 and 796 AD. It's believed that construction was started around 785 AD but it's not known if the Dyke represented an agreed border or a defensive structure. However, some sections still form the England\/Wales border more than twelve centuries later.\n\nRelations between the Welsh and the English haven't always been comfortable.  To quote George Borrow in ",{"type":"'''","value":["Wild Wales"]},": ",{"type":"''","value":["\"It was customary for the English to cut off the ears off every Welshman found east of the dyke, and for the Welsh to  hang every Englishman whom they found to the west of it.\""]},"  Thankfully it's more civil these days.\n\nThere is much variety in the route, passing as it does through historic towns such as Knighton, Kington, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hay-on-Wye"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Monmouth (Wales)"],["Monmouth"]]},", some wide river valleys, moorlands, remote villages and woodlands. The route passes near old forts and castles, including famous ruins such as ",{"type":"[[","value":[[":w:Tintern Abbey"],["Tintern Abbey"]]}," near ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Chepstow"]]},".\n\nAll of Offa’s Dyke Path follows legally defined Rights of Way for all walkers and is clearly signed with an acorn symbol. Some, but not all, sections are also available for horseriders and cyclists.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Prepare"]},"\nThe route is quite convoluted in some places so a set of ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk\/ Ordinance Survey"]}]}," maps covering the area would be a help.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get In"]},"\nThe north trailhead is at ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Prestatyn"]]}," which is 0.5km (0.3mi) from the train station.\n\nThe south trailhead is at Sedbury Cliffs, near ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Chepstow"]]},". The train station at Chepstow is about 3km (2mi) from the trailhead where there is a commemorative marker, about a mile east of Chepstow on the east side of the River Wye.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Walk"]},"\nThere are many types of accommodation along the route, including inns, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bed and Breakfast"],["B&Bs"]]},", campsites, hostels and self-catering facilities. \n\nListed below are a very small selection of things to see and do, places to stay and where to find food.\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["Mapframe"],["52.39"],["-3.07"],["width=350"],["height=1180"],["zoom=9"],["layer=MH"]]},"\nA sample 12-day walking itinerary from north to south would be as follows:\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"{{","value":[["marker"],["type=go"],["name=Prestatyn"],["lat=53.34230"],["long=-3.41267"]]}," to ",{"type":"'''","value":["Bodfari"]}," - 21km (13mi)"]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"{{","value":[["eat"],["name=Downing Arms Inn"],["alt="],["url="],["email="],["address=Mold Road, Bodfari LL16 4DW"],["lat=53.22093"],["long=-3.35225"],["directions="],["phone=+44 1745 710265"],["tollfree="],["fax="],["hours="],["price="],["content="]]}]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"{{","value":[["sleep"],["name=Valeside B&B"],["alt="],["url=http:\/\/valeside.wix.com\/valeside"],["email="],["address=Bella Vista, Tremeirchion Road, Bodfari LL16 4EG"],["lat=53.22236"],["long=-3.36295"],["directions=B5429, Bodfari"],["phone=+44 1745 710495"],["tollfree="],["fax="],["checkin="],["checkout="],["price=Sgl £50, dbl £75, twin £80"],["content=2 dbl (one ",{"type":"''","value":["en suite"]},"), 1 ",{"type":"''","value":["en suite"]}," twin."]]}]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["sleep"],["name=Station House Caravan Park"],["alt="],["url=http:\/\/www.stationhousecaravanpark.co.uk"],["email="],["address=Station House, Bodfari LL16 4DA"],["lat=53.21978"],["long=-3.36053"],["directions="],["phone=+44 1745 710372"],["tollfree="],["fax="],["price="],["checkin="],["checkout="],["content=Campground with a local pub nearby."]]}]}]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"{{","value":[["marker"],["type=go"],["name=Bodfari"],["lat=53.21976"],["long=-3.35958"]]}," to ",{"type":"'''","value":["Llandegla"]}," - 27km (17mi)"]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"{{","value":[["eat"],["name=The Plough Inn"],["alt="],["url=http:\/\/theploughgresford.co.uk"],["email="],["address=Ruthin Rd, Wrexham"],["lat=53.05775"],["long=-3.18470"],["directions=A525 near Llandegla